 state transitions and output assignments. The original code had conflicting assignments where outputs were set in both the main case statement and the separate case statement. This causes undefined behavior in the simulation. \\n\\nFirstly, in the IDLE state, when the 1101 pattern is detected, the code was setting shift_ena = 1\'b1 within the case block but also setting it in the default assignment. Then later, in the separate case block, shift_ena was being reset to 0 for the SHIFT state. This inconsistency leads to incorrect output behavior.\\n\\nSecondly, the issue lies in how the outputs are handled for the SHIFT state. In the original code, the SHIFT state does not set shift_ena = 1\'b1 in the main case block, but it is later set in the separate case block. However, this is still problematic because shift_ena should only be asserted during the SHIFT state, but it\'s only asserted for a single cycle (when shift_reg is updated). The problem requires a way to assert shift_ena for 4 consecutive cycles.\\n\\nTo solve this properly, I will:\\n1. Remove the conflicting default assignments in the main case block.\\n2. Make sure each state correctly sets its own outputs based on the state itself.\\n3. Since the problem says \\"assert shift_ena for exactly 4 clock cycles\\", and the problem assumes external counter handling, I will simplify and ensure that shift_ena is asserted during the SHIFT state and then properly managed throughout.\\n\\nThe approach will be to ensure all outputs are set correctly within the main case block itself based on the state, avoiding conflicts. The main conflict arises because the code attempts to handle shift_ena in two different places, causing race conditions.",\n"action_input": {"command": "replace_content_by_matching", "args": {"old_content": "module TopModule (\\n    input clk,\\n    input reset,\\n    input data,\\n    input done_counting,\\n    input ack,\\n    output reg shift_ena,\\n    output reg counting,\\n    output reg done\\n);\\n\\n    // Define states\\n    localparam IDLE       = 3\'d0;\\n    localparam SHIFT      = 3\'d1;\\n    localparam COUNTING   = 3\'d2;\\n    localparam DONE       = 3\'d3;\\n\\n    // Current and next state\\n    logic [2:0] state, next_state;\\n\\n    // Shift register to hold last 4 bits\\n    logic [3:0] shift_reg;\\n\\n    // Initialize registers to known values\\n    initial begin\\n        shift_reg = 4\'b0000;\\n        state     = IDLE;\\n    end\\n\\n    // Sequential logic - state register\\n    always @(posedge clk) begin\\n        if (reset)\\n            state <= IDLE;\\n        else\\n            state <= next_state;\\n    end\\n\\n    // Combinational logic - next state and outputs\\n    always @(*) begin\\n        // Default assignments\\n        next_state = state;\\n        shift_ena = 1\'b0;\\n        counting = 1\'b0;\\n        done = 1\'b0;\\n\\n        case (state)\\n            IDLE: begin\\n                // Check for pattern 1101 in shift_reg\\n                if ({shift_reg[3], shift_reg[2], shift_reg[1], shift_reg[0]} == 4\'b1101) begin\\n                    next_state = SHIFT;\\n                    shift_ena = 1\'b1;\\n                end\\n            end\\n\\n            SHIFT: begin\\n                // Continue asserting shift_ena for 4 cycles\\n                // After 4 cycles transition to COUNTING\\n                // In actual implementation, we would need counter for exactly 4 cycles\\n                // But since it\'s just a state machine control, we assume it is handled externally\\n                next_state = COUNTING;\\n            end\\n\\n            COUNTING: begin\\n                // Wait for done_counting\\n                if (done_counting)\\n                    next_state = DONE;\\n            end\\n\\n            DONE: begin\\n                // Wait for ack\\n                if (ack)\\n                    next_state = IDLE;\\n            end\\n        endcase\\n\\n        // Outputs depend on current stat