itional_kwargs={}, blocks=[TextBlock(block_type='text', text='{"reasoning":"The problem is with how shift_ena is handled in the combinational logic block. At the start of the combinational block, shift_ena is reset to 1\'b0. Then, in the IDLE state, when the 1101 pattern is detected, shift_ena is set to 1\'b1 in the same block. However, because the `next_state` is also set to `SHIFT`, the very next evaluation of the combinational block will see `state` as `SHIFT`, and thus the `case (state)` block will execute and set `shift_ena = 1\'b1` again. The problem arises in the timing and evaluation order which might not reflect the expected behavior correctly in simulation.\\n\\nTo address this, I\'m changing the approach to:\\n1. Remove the explicit setting of shift_ena in the IDLE state. The detection of 1101 just triggers the state transition.\\n2. Only set shift_ena in the SHIFT state block itself, ensuring it is asserted correctly during that state.\\n3. Ensure that other outputs (counting and done) are also set correctly based on their respective states.\\n\\nThis change ensures there is no ambiguity in how shift_ena is being driven and should align better with the expected behavior in the testbench.",\n"action_input": {"command": "replace_content_by_matching", "args": {"old_content": "    // Combinational logic - next state and outputs\\n    always @(*) begin\\n        // Default assignments\\n        next_state = state;\\n        shift_ena = 1\'b0;\\n        counting = 1\'b0;\\n        done = 1\'b0;\\n\\n        case (state)\\n            IDLE: begin\\n                // Check for pattern 1101 in shift_reg\\n                if ({shift_reg[3], shift_reg[2], shift_reg[1], shift_reg[0]} == 4\'b1101) begin\\n                    next_state = SHIFT;\\n                    shift_ena = 1\'b1;\\n                end\\n            end\\n\\n            SHIFT: begin\\n                // Continue asserting shift_ena for 4 cycles\\n                // After 4 cycles transition to C